## PREAMBLE: THE ATOM AS A MODELLING MANIFOLD

The Geofont 13 Information Geometry provides a deterministic mapping from discrete sequential data through complex phase space to volumetric structure. The electron shell of an atom is a natural physical realization of this geometry.

---

## PART I: THE ATOM AS A GEOFONT 13 MANIFOLD

### I.1 The 13-Node Angular Lattice as Angular Momentum Quantization

In quantum mechanics, the angular momentum of an electron in an atom is quantized. The Geofont 13-node lattice provides a natural discretization of the unit circle into 13 equally spaced angles:

$$\alpha_n = \frac{2\pi(n-1)}{13}, \quad n = 1,\dots,13$$

This corresponds to a quantization of angular momentum with $m_\ell$ values ranging from $-6$ to $+6$ (13 total values).

---

## PART II: MAXWELL'S EQUATIONS IN THE GEOFONT FRAMEWORK

### II.1 Gauss's Law: Charge Distribution in the 93-Node Matrix

The charge density $\rho$ is distributed across the 93-node icosahedral phase matrix. The divergence of the electric field at any point in the atom is determined by the net charge enclosed.

### II.2 Faraday's Law: Changing Orbitals and Induced Fields

$$\nabla \times \mathbf{E} = -\frac{\partial \mathbf{B}}{\partial t}$$

When an electron transitions between energy levels, the changing magnetic field induces a circulating electric field. This corresponds to the wave propagation along the 26-unit hypotenuse, with the Hades null at $s=13$ representing the point of maximum change.

---

## PART III: THE ELECTROMAGNETIC WAVE EQUATION

### III.1 Wave Propagation in the Atomic Cavity

The Geofont hypotenuse $S$, parameterized by $s \in [1, 26]$, serves as the propagation path for electromagnetic waves in the atomic cavity. The wave function is:

$$\Psi(s) = \frac{1}{s} \sin\left(\frac{\pi(s-1)}{12} + \varphi_0\right)$$

---

## PART IV: THE 93-NODE MATRIX AS ELECTRON CLOUD TOPOLOGY

### IV.1 Icosahedral Symmetry in Atomic Orbitals

The 93-node icosahedral phase matrix mirrors the symmetry of atomic orbitals:
- **$s$ orbitals**: Central node
- **$p, d, f$ orbitals**: Combinations of vertices, face centres, and edges.

